### CSS Position

**position** controls how an element is placed in the document.

---

### Position Values

| Value | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| `static` | Default - normal document flow |
| `relative` | Offset from normal position |
| `absolute` | Positioned relative to nearest positioned ancestor |
| `fixed` | Positioned relative to viewport |
| `sticky` | Toggles between relative and fixed |

---

### Positioning Properties

```css
/* Used with non-static positioning */
top: 10px;
right: 20px;
bottom: 30px;
left: 40px;
```

---

### Static (Default)

```css
position: static;
/* top/left/right/bottom have NO effect */
```

---

### Relative

```css
position: relative;
top: 20px;
left: 20px;
/* Shifted from normal position, original space preserved */
```

---

### Absolute

```css
position: absolute;
top: 0;
left: 0;
/* Removed from flow, positioned relative to nearest positioned ancestor */
```

If no ancestor has `position: relative/absolute/fixed/sticky`, it positions relative to `<html>`.

---

### Fixed

```css
position: fixed;
top: 0;
width: 100%;
/* Stays in place even when scrolling */
```

---

### Sticky

```css
position: sticky;
top: 0;
/* Behaves as relative until scroll reaches top:0, then becomes fixed */
```

---

### Common Patterns

```css
/* Badge on card */
.card {
  position: relative;
}
.badge {
  position: absolute;
  top: -10px;
  right: -10px;
}

/* Fixed navbar */
.navbar {
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  width: 100%;
  z-index: 100;
}

/* Sticky header */
.section-header {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  background: white;
  z-index: 10;
}
```

> **Key Point:** `absolute` positions relative to the **nearest positioned ancestor** (not the parent!). Set `position: relative` on parent containers to create a positioning context.
